Merry Christmas! This one needed a permanent spot on the feed! Yes, it was actually cold enough to wear my Delaney Sweater Dress to church! A Christmas miracle! ❤️❤️🤣

What I Wear Under My Crochet Dresses So Nothing Shows Through!
.
I often get asked how in the world I wear a crochet dress. Aren't I worried that everything will show through the stitches? So I finally made this little reel to show what I do to avoid any mishaps. 😊
.
If it's warm I'll wear a tank top and biker shorts. The shorts are fitted and short enough to hold everything in and not show any lines. If it's cold, I wear leggings, which do the same. I'll usually also wear a tank top under just so there's no bra lines or straps showing.
.
You cold also wear a slip or very thin spaghetti strap dress under a crochet dress. That would be a good option for sleeveless summer dresses. 
.
So there you have it! No need to worry about anything showing through! Go make all the dresses! 😆
.
Pattern: Delaney Sweater Dress ...can be found in both my Ravelry and Etsy shops. 
.
.
.
.
.

Are you like me and kinda love some of the sweaters in my book, "Crochet Makes for Men"? And maybe want to make one for yourself? Well, you can!
.
All of the patterns in my book are based off men's sizing from the Craft Yarn Council, but it's easy to customize them for women. 
1. Use chest measurement as your main measurement to go off of. Choose the one closest to your bust size. 
2. Then check finished measurement. You may find that it will be a bit oversized and can manage to go down a size. 
3. Be prepared to make adjustments. You likely won't need to make the garment as long as the pattern says to make it, and you may need to go up a hook size in areas like the hips.

*Tips for crocheting for Kids*
.
Ahead of the Kids Dutton Hoodie release next week, I want to share some tips and things I've learned about crocheting childrens garments. (And I may repeat them next week too, because they are that important!)
.
1. Size up. And size up from the size your kiddo measures accurately, not just the size they typically wear. CYC children's size chart is a bit different than what the typical size they wear so check the size chart in the pattern, measure your kiddo to see which measurements they are closest to and then size up! I promise you'll thank me later. Kids grow so fast!
2. Try on OFTEN! Do not crochet the whole thing and then try it on the kid. Bad idea. Trust me. 
3. Adjust as needed! For children's garments I'd say it's even more important to know how to make adjustments where needed. Too short? Adjust the length. Too tight? Adjust your hook size or st count. I have tons of resources on my blog and YouTube channel on how to adjust crochet garments to fit. Check them out. 😊
.
Hope these help! What else would you add?

"My guy won't wear anything I crochet him"
.
But could it be that maybe you're not crocheting the right thing?😬 Now I get it...some men don't wear sweaters at all...even store bought. But hear me out....
.
I've found for myself and for the people I'm crocheting for....thinner is better. My husband's favorite hat is made of sport weight yarn and his favorite sweater is fingering weight. Garments made in lighter weights feel nicer, aren't as hot, and lay or drape so much better. You can really achieve the look and feel of something you'd buy at the store with a lighter weight yarn. 
.
And depending on the complexity and stitch of the pattern, it usually doesn't take much longer to make! Maybe give it a try...I have hats in fingering and sport weight for a quick project to try. 
.
Who else is team lightweight like me?! 😆🙋‍♀️
.
.
.
.
.
